{
  "texts": [
    "LaPool (Noutahi et al. 1905) is a differentiable pooling that considers both graph structure and node features.",
    "It uses the Laplace transform of the graph to select a set of nodes as cluster centers, dynamically layer the graph, and then uses the attention mechanism to sparsely distribute the remaining nodes to each cluster.",
    "MemPool (Khasahmadi et al. 2020a) proposes a joint graph representation learning and graph coarsening memory layer that utilizes multiple sets of memory keys and convolution operations in this memory layer to achieve a soft assignment matrix, which does not necessarily require connectivity information.",
    "In addition, it relies on global information and therefore does not suffer from the over-smoothing problem.",
    "Non-Negative Matrix Factorization (NMF) (Bacciu and Di Sotto 2019) uses the NMF and Gram matrices of graph adjacency matrices to learn the node soft assignment matrices."
  ]
}